  "prompt": "Do questions on Quora that are non-anonymous get more distribution when posted as a follow-up to another question?",
  "response": "Quora's distribution algorithm can be complex and influenced by various factors, including user engagement, topic relevance, and timing. In general, follow-up questions (whether anonymous or non-anonymous) can potentially get more distribution if they are closely related to the original question and if the original question has garnered significant attention and activity.\n\nHere are some factors that can affect the distribution of non-anonymous follow-up questions on Quora:\n\n1. **Relevance**: If the follow-up question is highly relevant to the original question and adds significant value to the ongoing discussion, it is likely to garner more attention.\n\n2. **Popularity**: Questions linked to popular or highly viewed original questions may benefit from increased visibility. Users who engage with the original question may be more likely to notice and interact with follow-up questions.\n\n3. **Engagement**: Higher engagement (views, upvotes, answers, comments, shares) on the original question can lead to a spillover effect, where related follow-up questions also receive more attention.\n\n4. **User Profile**: Non-anonymous questions allow users to see who posted the question. If the user asking the follow-up question has a reputable profile with a high follower count or past history of quality contributions, it can attract more interest.\n\n5. **Timing**: The timing of posting the follow-up question can also influence distribution. Posting when the original question is actively being discussed or has just received new answers can increase visibility.\n\nUltimately, while follow-up questions have the potential to benefit from the attention generated by the original question, their success depends on how they align with the factors mentioned above.",
